ignish Castle, Argyll, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","London, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","Dunollie Castle, Argyll, Scotland":"Dunollie, Argyll and Bute, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MacDougall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:  see  McDougall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McDougall","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Dubhghaill</b>, ‘son of <i>Dubhghall</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>dubh</i> ‘black’ + <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’. This was originally a byname used to distinguish the darker-haired Danes from the fair-haired Norwegians. Compare   McDowell   and   Doyle  ."]}]},{"name":"Alan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Alan MacDougall 7th. of Dunollie was born in 1267, in Dunollie, Argyll and Bute, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Duncan MacDougall 6th of Dunollie and Joan MacDougall. He married Lady Christina MacNaughton about 1290, in Argyll, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in June 1320, in London, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1267–June 1320":"1267–juuni 1320","1267–1320":"1267–1320","1247–1310":"1247–1310","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1244–1320":"1244–1320","–Female":"Surnud","1247":"1247","January 131